# The network stack & the socket

Every network task comes back to one endpoint: the **socket** — where a program plugs into the network.

```
your program ─┐
              ▼
   socket = IP : port / protocol     93.184.216.34 : 443 / TCP
              │
 interface ─▶ routing ─▶ gateway ─▶ the wider internet
              │
 name → address (DNS) · who can reach me (firewall)
```

## To send a packet, Linux needs

- an **address** on an **interface**
- a **route** (which interface + gateway)
- **DNS** (name → address)
- a **firewall** rule (who may connect)

## Then use it securely — SSH

Half the module is **SSH** end to end — the universal remote-admin protocol: connection & host keys, key auth, config & agent, `sshd`, `scp`/`rsync`.

Modern tools throughout: **`ip`** (addresses/routes) · **`ss`** (sockets). `ifconfig`/`netstat` are deprecated.
